<p><strong> California Vole (<em>Microtus californicus</em>)</strong></p>
<p><strong>Family: </strong>Cricetidae<br />
<strong>Genus Species: </strong><em>Microtus californicus</em><br />
<strong>Common Name: </strong>California Vole<br /><p>
<p><strong>Identification</strong></p>
<p>The California Vole has a length of 4¾-5⅔ inches, a tail length of 1⅗-2⅘ inches, and a weight of 42-100 grams. It is grayish brown, but usually are blackish towards the coast and reddish in the desert. It has a bicolored tail and pale feet. For a more detailed overview of this species see 〔<a href="http://www.enature.com/fieldguides/detail.asp?allSpecies=y&amp;searchText=california%20vole&amp;curGroupID=5&amp;lgfromWhere=&amp;curPageNum=1" target="_blank">eNature</a>〕.</p>
<p><strong> </strong></p>
<p><strong>Habitat Associations and Natural History</strong></p>
<p>This vole can be found in marshy grounds, salt and fresh waters, wet meadows, dry or grassy hillsides, along seashores, and up in mountains. It bears 4-8 young more than once a year and has a gestation period of 21 days. It feeds on grasses, sedges, and other green vegetation. Its main predators are hawks, owls, weasels, and snakes.<br />
